supportDesc.condition: andhave text on the verso vaguely visible through the parchment. The flyleaves have detached in the corners where some of the text is visible. The text has left an offprint on the boards.

p.note: Top left corner: National Library book label with current signum; top of page in brown ink by a medieval hand: Pertinet bernardus hannegren (?); below, in brown ink by a medieval hand: a table of contents; bottom of page: a glued on fragment from another document with text in Latin.

binding.p: Medieval or early modern binding. Leather over cardboard. 3 double raised bands and endbands. , four papers labels, three of which are pasted over older labels. From top to bottom: N. 18, 56., (155); No 16. Hic Lyrani commentarius in Epistolas Pauli et Apocalypin; stamped in gold: A 156; 16; e 30. 3. 3.. , traces of a label on the upper part of the cover. There are also traces of writing in black ink directly on the cover.
binding.condition: Leather extremley worn. Boards exposed in several places. Holes in covers after corner pieces or bosses and probably also clasps.

history.origin: Austria? , 14th century, middle of. The place of origin and dating are tentatively based on the watermark.
history.provenance: Early provenance unknown. On a medieval hand states that the book belongs to one Bernardus Hannegren(?). The manuscript has been at the National Library since at least the 17th century. Most of the signa on the spine correspond to older catalogues at the library. The manuscript is listed in Jaches's catalogue of of 1695 (U 118:10) as 155, and in the catalogue of 1698 (U 122) as 56; as 16 in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e); and as e. 30. 3. 3. in Hammarsköld's catalogue of the 19th century (U 133). The signum 18 has not been identified.

msItem.title: Questio ad probandum Christi aduentum
